value.value: Loss of alertness and orientation to place and time.
Muscular atrophy affecting the lower limb.
Functional neurological abnormalities related to dysfunction of the pyramidal tract.

definition.value: Presence of these signs can indicate affection of the corticospinal (pyramidal) tracts.

value.value: Atrophy affecting the cerebellum and the spinocerebellar tracts of the spinal cord.
A loss of myelin from nerve fibers in the central nervous system.

definition.value: CNS demyelination affects the white matter, which consists mostly of axons with their envelope of myelin, along with two types of neuroglia: oligo-dendrocytes and astrocytes.

value.value: Reduced ability to perceive painful stimuli.
Underdevelopment of the frontal lobe of the cerebrum.
Weakness of the muscles of the legs.

definition.value: Inability to perform rapid, alternating movements.

value.value: A focal-onset seizure is a type of seizure originating within networks limited to one hemisphere. They may be discretely localized or more widely distributed, and may originate in subcortical structures.

definition.value: In 2017 the ILAE Commission for Classification and Terminology recommended classifying a seizure as having focal or generalized onset only when there is a high degree of confidence (>80%, arbitrarily chosen to parallel the usual allowable beta error) in the accuracy of this determination; see Dialeptic seizure.

label.value: Atrophy/Degeneration affecting the central nervous system

value.value: Absence or underdevelopment of the corpus callosum.
Abnormal thickening of the skin on the palms and soles charactersized by hyperkeratosis of the stratum corneum with no evidence of epidermolysis characteristic of epidermolytic hyperkeratosis.
An abnormally increased perspiration on palms and soles.
The presence of two to five cafe-au-lait macules.
The presence of multiple leiomyomas of the skin.
A type of blistering that affects the skin of the palms of the hands and the soles of the feet.
Diffuse abnormal thickening of the skin on the palms and soles.

definition.value: The terms hyperkeratosis and keratoderma have been used interchangeably throughout the literature.

value.value: The presence of six or more cafe-au-lait spots.
The presence of leiomyoma of the skin.

definition.value: Cutaneous leiomyomata are benign soft tissue neoplasms that arise from smooth muscle cells in the skin.

value.value: A developmental anomaly characterized by abnormal smallness of both eyes.
A type of cataract with punctate opacities of the lens.
Congenital underdevelopment of the iris.
A functional abnormality of the pupil.

definition.value: It is preferable to describe the functional defect precisely.

value.value: A unilateral form of ptosis.
Abnormal development (dysgenesis) of the anterior segment of the eye globe. These structures are mainly of mesenchymal origin.

definition.value: In anterior segment mesenchymal ocular dysgenesis (ASMOD), multiple tissues are affected, including the iris, cornea, and lens as well as the Schlemm's canal and trabecular meshwork drainage structures located at the anterior segment angle where the iris and cornea meet. These abnormalities may result from a primary defect in the migration and/or differentiation of the mesenchymal cells that contribute to development of the cornea, iris, and drainage structures.

value.value: Absence of the crystalline lens of the eye as a result of a developmental defect.
A malignant melanoma originating within the eye. The tumor originates from the melanocytes in the uvea (which comprises the iris, ciliary body, and choroid).

definition.value: WIth intraocular melanoma, the melanoma originates from melanocytic cells in the uveal layer, comprising the iris, ciliary body, and choroid.

value.value: Atrophy (loss or wasting) of the retinal pigment epithelium observed on fundoscopy or fundus imaging.
Abnormal (non-physiological) constriction of the pupil of congenital onset.
Underdevelopment of the fovea centralis.

definition.value: A dull foveal reflex is an unusual reflex of the foveal region on fundoscopy that may indicate hypoplasia of the fovea.

value.value: Macular dystrophy is a nonspecific term for premature retinal cell aging and cell death, generally confied to the macula in which no clear extrinsic cause is evident.
Ocular abnormality characterized by premature degeneration of the vitreous and the retina that may be associated with increased risk of retinal detachment.

definition.value: Fibrous connective tissue resulting from incomplete healing of a wound (i.e., a scar) located in the choroid and retina or the eye.

value.value: A type of cataract characterized by punctate, dust-like opacities within the cortical region of the lens.

The presence of central, fine, whitish granular lesions in the stroma of the cornea. This type of corneal dystrophy is usually asymptomatic and begins in childhood and shows a slow progression. Later in the course, the corneal epithelium and Bowman's layer may be affected. Histologically, the cornea shows a uniform deposition of hyaline material.
Complete color blindness, a complete inability to distinguish colors. Affected persons cannot perceive colors, but only shades of gray.

definition.value: Rod monochromacy is the condition of having only rods in the retina. A rod monochromat is truly unable to see any color and can see only shades of gray.

value.value: Inability to see well at night or in poor light with onset in adulthood.
Punched out lesions in the pigmented layer of the retina.

definition.value: A chorioretinal lacuna can have the appearance of a pseudodisk in the retina.

value.value: Congenital abnormal dilation of the pupil on both sides.
